docs/review-packets/T-001.5-standards-blindspot-review.md:107:**Reject (process bloat):** standalone source-scan log, evidence matrix, framework selection matrix, standing assumption log, failure-taxonomy doc, standing blindspot log, "deep rationale always." **Defer to the stage that needs them:** integration security checklist (RLS/webhook-signing/least-privilege — already captured in `codex-initial-review` for later), operational cost/budget ledger rules, reliability/observability (retries/timeouts), the evaluation harness itself (that is T-002's candidate work, not a playbook rule), data-privacy/PII and accessibility (no real data / no UI yet).
docs/review-packets/T-001.5-standards-blindspot-review.md:111:**Proceed to create T-001.5 — in the reduced single-playbook form above — after closing T-001's three open follow-ups** (the `out/` volatile-log policy, the `v1-slice-plan` test-list doc-sync, and the git-state checklist step), so the playbook isn't built on an unclosed stage. If the team insists on the full 15-artifact version, **do not proceed** — it would convert the project's strongest asset (disciplined, source-backed reasoning) into the liability it already warned against (governance outpacing product). The honest test for the playbook: it should make the *next* task faster and more traceable, not add paperwork to it.
