     8	public disclosure is appropriate), or use GitHub's private vulnerability reporting
     9	on the repo if you prefer.
    10	
    11	## What the threat surface actually is
    12	
    13	- **The website** is a static export of committed, labeled fixtures. It initiates
    14	  no sends, makes no live calls, and holds no secrets. There is no server.
    15	- **The verifier runtime** is deterministic TypeScript with no AI calls and no
    16	  network calls — enforced by import-graph tests
    17	  (`evals/crew/crew-import-walk.test.ts`), not by policy.
    18	- **Secrets**: none are committed (RULES.md §11). Live-leg runs read keys from a
    19	  gitignored `.env`; contact data in fixtures is fake by construction.
    20	
    21	## MCP server threat posture
    22	
    23	The repo ships an MCP server (`bin/mcp-server.mjs`) exposing the verifier through
    24	the typed tool registry. Its posture, stated plainly:
    25	
    26	1. **Stdio-only transport** — no network listener exists to attack; the server
    27	   only talks to the local client that spawned it.
    28	2. **Read-only, deterministic tools** — every advertised tool routes through the
    29	   typed JSON-schema-validated registry (`lib/tools/registry.ts`) into the
    30	   deterministic engine; there is no tool that sends, spends, mutates state, or
    31	   touches the network (the same import-graph walk covers modules reachable from
    32	   the registry).
    33	3. **Tool-description integrity** — the schemas the server advertises are the
    34	   committed registry schemas verbatim; a recorded transcript
    35	   (`evals/mcp/`) pins what a real session sees, so silent tool-description drift
    36	   (the classic MCP tool-poisoning vector) is test-visible.
    37	4. **Content-as-data discipline** — fixture and feed content processed by the
    38	   tools is treated as data to verify, never as instructions to follow; the crew's
    39	   containment contract (steered-model blocking, human-gate forcing) is
    40	   eval-locked (`evals/crew/`).
    41	5. **What is NOT claimed**: no authentication layer (unnecessary for a local
    42	   stdio prototype), no multi-tenant isolation, no production hardening — this is
    43	   a demonstration server for a prototype, and a real deployment would need its
    44	   own review. A signed-action approvals flow is designed as an offline simulator
    45	   (plan E3) and is not a live capability.
