app/legacy/merchant/[id]/page.tsx:133:          plain="A bounded, schema-constrained draft. Here it's the deterministic stub (REPLAY); a recorded real-Gemini run is on the Eval page — the safety machinery around it is identical either way."
app/legacy/merchant/[id]/page.tsx:182:          plain="A second, independent check: an LLM from a DIFFERENT model family reads the finished message and verifies each factual sentence against the merchant's data row — catching an invented number, capability, or timeline the deterministic gatekeeper structurally can't see. Here it's the deterministic stub verdict (REPLAY, $0); the live cross-family judge (Groq gpt-oss-120b) is key-gated."
app/legacy/merchant/[id]/page.tsx:228:          plain="A third, independent check — on a different question than faithfulness. Not 'is every fact true?' but 'is this a GOOD activation message?' — scored against a cited rubric: matched to the merchant's real blocker · the right play for their engagement state · no over-promising. It's advisory and recall-favoring: the verdict is surfaced for the reviewer and recorded in the audit trail, but it never changes the send — eligibility and the human approval gate stay deterministic (a low-risk draft can still be simulated-sent even when flagged). Here BOTH the draft and this verdict are deterministic $0 stubs (REPLAY) — a minimal stub nudge often trips the engagement-fit check, which is the tertiary control doing its job, not the product grading its real output down; the live cross-family judge (Groq gpt-oss-120b) and the real drafter are separate and key-gated."
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:14:- **Phase 3 replaces only `make_draft()`** ([scripts/pipeline.py:112](../scripts/pipeline.py:112)) — the generated *text* (`risk_explanation`, `blocker_summary`, `draft_subject`, `draft_body`). **No golden field observes that text.** A Gemini swap leaves "MERCHANT 20/20" unchanged by construction.
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:60:- **Generator-agnostic (Codex P1 + round-1 #1 — the acceptance must have teeth, not just the design):** the contract runs **unchanged** against `make_draft` (stub) now and the Gemini step later. Concretely: (a) the fixtures include **positive paraphrased-"good" drafts, ≥1 per blocker/action type, hand-written NOT produced by `make_draft()`** (so a real-but-differently-phrased good draft must score as good); (b) a test **asserts no fixture contains `make_draft()`'s literal template strings** (mechanical guard against the contract encoding the stub); (c) scoring keys on **invariants** (does the draft reference the merchant's actual blocker / next-action / step-count?), **never on phrasing**. `validate_draft()` today mostly checks non-empty fields — S2 adds the state-consistency invariant check on top.
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:62:- **Success metric:** a recorded draft-quality score, ~100% on the stub today (by construction), which Phase 3's model output must **meet or beat behind the guardrails**. This becomes the real pre-Gemini baseline number (recorded in the v2 baseline once S3 lands; recorded against v1 in the interim).
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:73:- **Synthetic edge-case overlay (quality):** add the safety-path rows by design so the canonical v2 run **exercises every path a viewer should see fire**: ≥1 `opted_out`, ≥1 non-empty `suppression_reason`, ≥1 malformed email (→ expected `review_reason = ineligible_contact`). **The `draft_rejected > 0` path is exercised in the S4 eval corpus, NOT in the live `make_draft` run (Codex round-1 #6):** `run_pipeline()` always calls the clean stub `make_draft()`, which never produces a policy-violating draft, so the guardrail can't reject in the live pipeline today. Planted bad drafts therefore live in the S4 adversarial corpus where the contract/guardrail scores them — the coverage matrix marks `draft_rejected` as an **eval-corpus path, not a demo-run path** (honest separation). **DoD reconciliation (Codex round-2 #6 — the ratified hold/reject/send walkthrough needs the reject path to be SHOWABLE):** the walkthrough demonstrates **reject** via an **S4 eval-corpus replay** — the demo surfaces a planted bad draft and the guardrail's rejection of it ("here is a draft the guardrail caught, with the reason") — labeled as an injected/eval case, distinct from the live deterministic run. This stays honest (no fake live rejection) **and** satisfies the DoD's three-path demo. Phase 3 (real Gemini) is the first point a *live* reject can occur naturally; until then, reject is demonstrated by replay. *(Roadmap/DoD note added so the walkthrough spec matches this.)* Malformed-email handling is **v2-only synthetic**: validation today rejects many malformed addresses upstream, so S3 defines exactly how a planted malformed-email row reaches `ineligible_contact` rather than being silently dropped.
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:78:- **Coverage matrix (published):** path → the exact row/case that exercises it — **demo-data coverage** (what the public live run shows) kept **distinct** from **eval-fixture coverage** (what the regression suite asserts, incl. the corpus-only `draft_rejected` path). Every metric labeled *simulated*.
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:89:- **Blocking secrets hook — a committed, nonzero-exit script, not advisory text (Codex round-1 #10–12).** Implement `scripts/check_secrets.py` (exit ≠ 0 on a hit). Wiring uses the **same mechanism as the git-state check** (below): primary path = run it as a committed close-out step; optional convenience = a tracked `.githooks/` pre-commit + `git config core.hooksPath .githooks` that calls it (since `.git/hooks` is untracked/sample-only). The script is the source of truth. Detector breadth is a **staged-file fixture matrix** covering the forms that actually matter — **`GEMINI_API_KEY=…` and current Gemini/env-key formats** (Phase 3's real key — verify the live format at build time, RULES §6), generic high-entropy tokens, **bearer/JWT-like** tokens, private-key blocks (`-----BEGIN … PRIVATE KEY-----`), `.env` assignments, JSON service-credential blobs, and DB **connection strings** (`postgres://…`). The current `pii_or_secret` detector misses several of these — S5 closes the gap with fixtures proving each blocks.
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:99:Any live Gemini/model call · real secrets · network at *runtime* (the one-time S3 dataset fetch is a build-time action, recorded + frozen) · new pip dependencies · modifying `tests/test_t001.py` / `tests/test_t002.py` (additive-only) · editing the v1 source CSV **content** or its golden/baseline (the OQ-1 filename rename via `git mv` + the `config.py:10` re-pin is the sole, owner-directed exception — content stays byte-identical) · real sends · 24/7/hosting/ops machinery (prototype identity) · paid tools (free-first; Gemini <$5 enters only at Phase 3). Phase 3 itself is the **next** task and is FULL workflow.
docs/phase3-prep-slice-plan.md:106:- **v2 lane (S3):** golden v2 hash-pin verified; **header-aware v2 adapter reads named columns while the positional v1 path is unchanged (#5)**; canonical v2 **live run** fires the demo safety paths (opted-out, suppression, malformed email → `ineligible_contact`); the **`draft_rejected > 0` path is asserted in the S4 eval corpus, not the live run (#6)**; **v2 outputs land in an isolated lane dir with `T-003` metadata — v1 `out/` untouched (#8)**; **`scripts/eval.py` produces the v2 numbers via lane/source args (#7)**; identical re-run idempotent; coverage matrix marks each path demo-run vs eval-corpus.
